Somewhat surprisingly, <span style="color: #000000;">Center</span> leader Adam Stegerwald is elected as the chairman of its successor party. This is largely attributed to the unified support from the various Christian labor unions and backing from former <span style="color: #000000;">Center</span> and Catholic politicians. However, he remains largely opposed by former <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span> members due to his willingness to cooperate constructively with the <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD**</span>.

It was widely expected that, with the merger of the two parties, politicians like Stegerwald would shift to the left wing of the newly created party—and this has indeed proven true. His strongest supporters, aside from the trade unions, include the now strengthened <span style="color: #FF7F00;">Christian Left</span> faction, which will push for a paternalistic economic policy and greater cooperation with the <span style="color: #c00000;">socialists</span>. Stegerwald is also a committed <span style="color: #000000;">rep</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">ubl</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ican</span>, a stance that has pushed some ardent monarchists over to the <span style="color: #003755;">**DNF**</span>.

