Somehow, the <span style="color: #6D5298;">Christian Socialist</span> wing, now diluted within a much larger party, has managed to elect one of their own as the leader of the <span style="color: #000000;">**[+ z_party_name +]**</span>. Walther Lambach, the writer of the Lambach article years ago[? if dnvp_leader == "Lambach":, and the most recent leader of the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>?], has won the vote largely due to the unified support of the Christian labor unions, who strongly back his vision for a *Volksgemeinschaft*.

More <span style="color: #c00000;">worker-friendly</span> policies have been added to the platform, such as expanding social welfare, increasing pensions, and implementing more progressive income taxes. They've even rejected austerity as a solution to Germany's current economic crisis, instead voicing support for public works. However, this has significantly strained industrial enthusiasm for the formation of the new party, and they have begun redirecting funds toward the <span style="color: #FFCC00;">liberals</span>.

This, however, is not good news for us. <span style="color: #6D5298;">Christian Socialist</span> ideology is deeply rooted in antisemitism, racism, nationalism, and religiosity. If anything, we've noticed worsening relations with the <span style="color: #000000;">**[+ z_party_name +]**</span>, as they attempt to present a non-<span style="color: #9B0000;">Marxist</span> alternative to the workers.

