Günther Gereke, a lawyer and prominent politician from rural Germany, has been elected as the new leader of the <span style="color: #000000;">**[+ z_party_name +]**</span>. What makes him notable is that he is an <span style="color: #385A38;">agrarian</span> politician from west of the Elbe River, a leading reformist economic theorist, and someone with close ties to General Kurt von Schleicher. He bears similarities to Treviranus, though he is far less dogmatic in his beliefs.

Thanks to Gereke’s strong relationship with the <span style="color: #7FCEB1;">**CNBLP**</span>, a rural special-interest party, he has successfully negotiated a merger of the declining party into the <span style="color: #000000;">**[+ z_party_name +]**</span>, though only a few officials remain in the effectively dead party. His support for a public works program has stemmed criticism from the labor factions, and his ability to unite the key interest groups on which the German Right depends on will help secure strong <span style="color: #3E88B3;">nationalist</span> backing for the party.

Needless to say, this has not sat well with the <span style="color: #000000;">**[+ z_party_name +]**</span>’s Catholic wing, and has made cooperation within the party impossible for the foreseeable future.

