Paul von Lettow-Vorbeck is a war hero renowned for his undefeated record and his successful guerrilla campaign in German East Africa, with victories that rival those of Hindenburg. Despite multiple attempts to involve him in German politics, he has remained largely inactive, serving as a member of the Reichstag elected under the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>. However, the [? if vorbeck_deadlock: unending deadlock at the congress?][? if not vorbeck_deadlock and vorbeck_decline: drastic decline in the moderate right's vote share?][? if not vorbeck_deadlock and not vorbeck_decline and vorbeck_presidential: desire to utilize his character for a potential future election run?] has led to a growing number of factions rallying around his candidacy. The widespread popular support for him draws strong parallels to Hindenburg's own presidential candidacy declaration in 1925.

Reluctantly, Lettow-Vorbeck has accepted the <span style="color: #000000;">**[+ z_party_name +]**</span>'s nomination as their next leader. However, he has little interest in managing the party’s internal affairs and has quietly delegated this responsibility to fellow conservatives like Westarp. Nonetheless, he remains the public face of the <span style="color: #000000;">**[+ z_party_name +]**</span> as chairman. The most crucial aspect of his election is his ability to inspire the German people to rally behind a WW1 war hero once again, someone who embodies the image of stability and unity. Time will tell how long this popularity will last.

It goes without saying, his election will make cooperation within the party impossible for the foreseeable future.